The Morality of Having Kids in a Magical, Maybe Simulated World
There=E2=80=99s a thing that fancy magazines do every so often, which is to=
 ask this Very Deep Question: is it morally OK to have kids when the planet=
 is literally burning?=C2=A0
I am here to tell you that that is an exceedingly dumb question.=C2=A0
I am here to tell you that you should have kids.
There are a bunch of rational arguments you can make against the idea that =
it=E2=80=99s immoral to have kids in a drowning, burning world:=C2=A0
Any one person=E2=80=99s emissions are negligible
More kids mean a greater chance that someone figures out new solutions to c=
limate change and all sorts of other challenges
Malthusian predictions have been wrong to date=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a Pascal=E2=80=99s Wager of sorts: if climate change destroys =
the planet, your downside is finite (we all die anyway); if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t, your upside is infinite (generations of your family will live in an e=
nergy abundant world and maybe even travel the galaxy)=C2=A0
Kids rock
But it=E2=80=99s December now, and we=E2=80=99re in that annual wind-down p=
eriod, so I figure why not get a little bit weird, try a different tack. It=
=E2=80=99s going to be one of these pieces:=C2=A0
The other day, thinking about that Very Big Question, I tweeted something c=
ryptic [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e77b45b-dcdd-4c98-9ca1-a4a5101d6069=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=
=80=9CThe climate crisis is the best proof I=E2=80=99ve seen that we=E2=80=
=99re in a simulation.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
A few people, understandably, asked me what the hell I was talking about.=
=C2=A0
The short, non-crazy version is this: climate change is a very real challen=
ge with very real negative impacts on people and the planet. But climate ch=
ange is solvable, and by solving it, we unlock the next phase of civilizati=
